title: Grateful Dead Live at Capital Centre on 1990-03-15
lineage: MC > standalone TDK DA-5800 CD recorder, via Nak BX-300 cassette deck, as long multi-song tracks, Transfer by Dave Hanscom; CDWav> EAC> shn by Bzl
description: Jack Straw, Sugaree, Easy To Love You, Walkin' Blues, Althea, Just Like Tom Thumb's Blues, Tennessee Jed, Cassidy, Don't Ease Me In China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Samson & Delilah, Terrapin Station-> Jam-> Drums-> Jam-> I Will Take You Home-> Wharf Rat-> Throwing Stones-> Not Fade Away, E: Revolution

reviews.review_text: phil's 50th birthday this show was so great in fact, that they released it as terrapin limited. good to have an audience also.
Great show Great show for 1990 and the Terrapin seemed to last forever(a good thing). Great way to warm us up for the historic 1990 Summer Tour. Some real gems within this show.

Does any one else here the tomorrow never knows? In the jam out of Terrapin it sounds to me like they are definately playing around with this theme- especially listening to Jerry and drums- the drummers would later pick up this beat when they started playing the song.
"." Nonintuitive "." Nonintuitive

Landover The whole run was killer, but tonight - Oh My GOD what a night to be standing right in the middle of the Phil Zone!! This was only my 5th show (priors being Greensboro 89, Hampton 89 (both) and Charlotte 89 and I remember being WOWED. It's amazing that 16 years later that Terrapin still sends a huge shiver up my spine - "Inspiration" - Indeed!!

this one ssmookeSS!! wow, hearing the sbd, then the aud. Hearing the aud after the sbd, and on a night when i went away from the computer and came back opened the file and didnt know the date. it just felt right, when i checked the info and it read march 15th i just smiled and said yeap. 5 frickn stars for brent and jerry. and bob. and billy and mickey.

Jam out of terrapin official titled 'mock turtle jam'


you want this show!!!! hands down.

Happy Birthday Phil!! hehe, this show's on Phil's Birthday

IÃÂÃÂm surprised they didn't play Happy Birthday for him seeing as it was his 50th birthday lol
Feelin' the VIBE!! Wow, you can just feel the energy at this show by listening to the audience. Some great moments here.

jerry & my cherry This was my first show. I was off to the side, stage left. There was a golden glowing halo atop Jerry's head for the later half of the second set. 
I cannot speak for the sound quality of this show, as I have not heard it (ever). My rating is based soley on the show itself. God & I both give it five stars.

GD 3/15/1990 Cap Center Landover: 
You will never find a more wretched hive of scum and villainy...
We must be cautious.
Yo, Maryland cops were TOUGH, boyee!

Hey, Boyd McHugh -- if there was ever a chance I could remember this specific show after all these years, and after so many Cap Center runs --- I know it would sound something like what you gave us here  - THANK YOU, BRUTHA!

Actually that's not true -- This Tom Thumbs was first I'd witnessed -- special -- and I kinda remember the Philbert Birthday Buzz in the lot...16 years ago and counting --- geez louise.

DC/ MD venues were really blessed with some pretty far out Philzone moments...
BACK TO FOGGY BOTTOM - I DO BELIEVE - 

Happy Daze, guys

3-15-90 It's hard to give anything from spring 90 a three star rating, but it is solely due to the sound (AUD). Although it is wonderfully nostalgic to hear the roar of the crowd. Performance is a 5. 
Phil's 50th. What a way to have spent his 50th Birthday, one of the luckiest people on earth.

Just listen to that crowd roar on the "This place is getting hot" line on Althea, I LOVE IT!!

After a ten year hiatus, Brent and the boys bust out the moth-balled Easy To Love You.

terrapin station 4 stars is based on the performance and not the recording. Try to find a better source. I actully have the official "terrapin station" 3 disc set and the sound is great. By the way boys....weren't the proceeds from those sales at 39.99 a pop suppose to go to a project called Terrapin station where fans could get copies of any show in the deads career? Not only do you not follow through and take the cash, but you shut this website down for a while then pull the soundboards. Sad to hear about Vince.

ROCKIN YO WHAT UP DOUGGIE/SHMEE!  I was at the show and the COPs were absolutely brutal but the BOYS were ON.  What a night and venue to play Revolution!  After all the shit we had to put up with, the REV. really hit the spot!  Can't wait to sink my ears into this one!  OJ
BTW- The rating is solely based on a very hazy memory of a rockin show!
terrapin five stars for the thrilling post-terrapin improvisation that makes this my all-time favorite terrapin station and one of my top shows of 1990.
Tugs on the heart strings How heart wrenching is Brent's I Will Take You Home? I love that the Grateful Dead can go from the psychedelia that is Space to the tear jerker I Will Take You Home.
Happy Birthday Phil!! great show all around.. love the feeling of this source.. thanks alot to everyonce involved getting this here. w00t!!
Terrapin This is my favorite version of Terrapin.  Its just so tight and strong.    Do yourself a favor and take a listen.

Terrapin Also my fav Terrapin ever..starts mellow and melodic, becomes intense, ends spacy...jam drifts from the theme and flows perfectly into drumz: nothing is rushed.  Check out Jerry's fill-ins during "Althea" in the 1st set - also a standout version.
Peace to your soul Brent... Peace to your soul Brent and thank you...
Terrapin Best Terrapin and Althea of all time!  In one night!

Best Throwing Stones ever! The energy built up by the drums during Weir's "We are on our own" vocal section must have inspired Garcia or something. Even amongst a great year of Throwing Stones, this jam makes it the best. When Garcia starts riffing you can hear in the intensity and true care he puts into this jam. Brent in turn is inspired by Jerry's sublime playing and busts out some sick piano riffs. Oh, and no this show does not have the best Wharf Rat (has anyone hear any shows from 5/77, I can think of about a dozen from that era that top this, musically and vocally.) still good, but not the best by any stretch.

By far one of the best.... This is without a doubt one of the BEST post drums I have ever heard...it speaks of truth and love and inspiration and REVOLUTION!  Starts with Brent, builds on Jerry, and Bob BRINGS it! but not without PHIL!!!  celebrating his fiftieth, and they all get to chime in on the encore.  AMAZING show...nuf said!   See for yourself...

Great random show I happened to click on the "This day in Dead history" link yesterday and got this show.... I love picking random shows and having them turn out to be an excellent experience. What a classic show!! Nice tempo, up beat, eager crowd, great versions of favorites and Phil's birthday.... NICE!!!

After all these years the music and this show is still relevant. Amazing!!!!

Going to see a couple nights of the 2009 spring tour and am psyched, although Jerry will be missed I'm sure Warren and the boys will rock the house!!!
I Know you rider There was something in the air that night@Copital Centre.5 bolts/////that is all.

Tom Thumb's Check out the end of Tom Thumb's just before they hit the final chord - Jerry plays a little "Happy Birthday to you" lick for Phil.

It warms my heart. Terrapin is sick also. Looking forward to Phil's 70th at the Bill Graham Civic!

terrapin what a great terrapin! the jam is smoking. the dead doing what they do best, a total original piece of improv. and very nicely done at that. the rolling, thundering drums, to the meandering guitar, to the driving sound of phil's bass....made up on the spot.

exellent One of my favorite shows.Terrapin was awesome!I sat 5th row,1st row on the 16th.I had actually lost my tickets in the parking lot before the show but amazingly found them on the ground 20 min. later surrounded buy a large group of people needing a miracle!The tickets had been run over, stepped on,ground in the dirt,but nobody bothered to look in the envelope.
 Definitely recommend this show!They were on that night!

Phil's 50th Have not listened to the sound yet. So this review is of the show. My first review. More of a story. I snuck into this show. Got super lucky. The tickets were almost impossible to get on the lot as one could tell. My friend and I drove from Kansas to the show with many problems. Car broke down. Spent almost all our money fixing it. Decided to go on anyway. Nicknamed the run "sping broke". It was spring break from KU. Made it in a smoking car. Overheated. I had given up trying to get in. But wanted to see the light show before I left peeking through the curtains of the hall through the glass doors of the centre. As I walked toward the doors to look. Some folks dressed nice. Probably got their tickets cause the were in the Washington scene were leaving. Knew they were gonna crack the door. I slipped right in and walked in white light right past the guard cause he was to busy watching the dancers in front of him. Thank goodness. Than ran to were I thought a girl I knew might be sitting. A newspaper student out of penn state. Meet her at RFK that summer.Hi Not even close to finding her but ended up straight in the back of the centre. Had taken some boomers earlier and because I was not expecting to be inside. Had a can budweiser and half a half pint of wild turkey on me. Cracked the beer. Now security was after me. Saw the bootleg bruski. So I turned around and saw the wall in back of the stadium. I was trapped. But not in Grateful Dead land. I ran up to the last row. Got down under the legs of the people in the seats and was planning on crawling backwards all the way down the row to the other side. It was drums so most people were sitting. Underneath about four people I looked up and said the Head."I'm from Kansas,Just snuck in. There's a secruity guard after me" He said cool and covered me with his legs. I most have just disapered to that security guard. Fun stuff. He than said after a minute or two that it was cool. I stood up pulled my ponytail down, took off my jacket so the guard couln't tell it was me. Thanked my new best buddy. Shot the wild turkey and that was that. There was one seat in the very back row up agaisnt the wall just waiting for me. I will never foget. I might have been the happiest dead head there. Give or take a few. I asked what they had played. Except for Easy to Love You, it was pretty standard so I knew we were still in for a birthday treat. When They started the encore I thought it might have been Deal. Instead I was blown away with Revolution. When Jerry sang "you know it's gonna be alright" I belived it with all my heart and still to this day will always remember those words. "alright, you know it's gonna be aright" What a night. I was on top of the world. That five song set was absolutley fantastic. Can't believe it's been Twenty years. Wow. Well that is it.

Best Rider ever? This has got to be one the greatest Rider's ever performed. There is certainly a reason why this show was picked by Phil for the Terrapin cd.  It is arguably the greatest show of the almost unbelievably strong Spring 1990 run.  Find me a better Terrapin, a better type II jam (after 1981), a lovelier and more powerful Wharf Rat, or more bubbly and smokin' Samson.  Bet you'd be hard-pressed.  

I was so very lucky to see the band 86 times and this was the second best set I ever saw after the legendary formerly the Warlocks 1989-10-09 Dark Star, Death Don't, Attics set.  This set and show are a very close second.  The recording is quite good and since Garcia's guitar and voice are a bit low in the official release, I'll take this one over that one in a pinch. 

They were pure magic at the Cap Center that spring and the magic never let up until the tragic loss of Mydland.  This is a stunning and wondrous look at this band at the peak of their maturity: ripe and delicious.

Seven stars at least! This show is incredible, and the sound--if I'm right and this is the one I downloaded--is unbelievable. On a good stereo, you are THERE, at possibly the hottest f---ing show I've ever heard.

I feel bad for repeating... what everyone has already said, but why not?  
 
This is one great show from the great spring of 1990.  Many great versions, from Althea and, yes, Walking Blues, to Wharf Rat and Throwing Stones and the sweet, if ragged (lyric-wise), Revolution.  

The creme de la creme, though, is the Tereapin and the jam afterward.  Proof that in their 25th year this band was capable of spontaneously pulling out a jam as transcendentally gorgeous and original as anything they, or anyone else, has ever played.  Listen good...this is some beautiful music.  Everyone shines on this one, and there are beautiful sounds everywhere.  

The second part of Drums, the track between drums And space on the "official" release, is also phenomenal.  

Hard to compare this to something like Fillmore West run of 1969--apples and oranges.  This deserves five stars on its own merit.

Good show, not so great recording I got reamed for bagging on the next nights show, but it didn't do it for me. This one does. The official release of this is excellent, btw. The boys play really well. Love the Terrapin, and ensuing jam. Revolution was a great encore. Much fun.

Very Good AUD In contrast with the LaPorte AUD available for this show, this(Nak300) is a more clean source. The crowd noise only pops up in select places, and the instrument/vocal levels are very good. It lacks the power of the LaPorte source, though if you are after a more clean, even ended AUD, LaPorte is not for you. 

The Hubbard AUD for this show is also on the opposite side of the tracks from the LaPorte source. It separates from this Nak300 source in that it is a bit more crisp and the instrument tones haven't lost as much of their biting edge as they have in this source. So while this is a very strong source, I would strongly recommend going with the Hubbard AUD if you are not looking for the big AUD style of the LaPorte.

With all the reviews already up on this AUD I don't really need to... But, for good measure, yes, this show is sprints up to the edge of the cliff and jumps off, sans parachute, without a 2nd thought. Everyone knows about the Terrapin, and it is one of the best, but here it is just one portion of an all together epic concert. Show is a full 5/5.
Spring 1990 Of all the shows I attended this particular night will always be 1 of my favorites. Great recording, Great memories

THE BEST AUD FOR THIS SHOW But not great by far. This source is decent, but it leaves much to be desired. I'm not sure why the Charlie Miller SBD is still down; Terrapin Limited was specifically a limited edition release, like the Dave's Picks series, and all of those boards are still up. Price gougers on eBay are asking $70 - $100 for this set. What a rip off. 

5 star show, 3 star sound.

Terrapin Jam! I really liked the Cassidy-Dont Ease Me In to close the 1st.  Jerry really belts it out. The best part by far is the Jam after Terrapin, it just keeps going.  I also like Brent coming out of Space with I  Will Take You Home, which he does nearly solo.  They dont really know where to go from there though because it cannot really turn into anything, so they switch quickly to Wharf Rat.
Tape speed This rendering is marred by a definite tape speed issue that makes the pitch too high and tempo too fast.  There are better audience editions out there.

hotsosohot Anyone who bad mouths this tape either has shit in his ears or is trying to listen to it on a smartphone in bed without waking the old lady. This show, this copy, loud, in a car (esp) or on a decent stereo, is one of the most transportive Dead listening experiences. The Terrapin Ltd. soundboard is merely a shadow of what you find here

Ahhh.... Mock Turtle Jam Gosh, that jam just makes me smile out loud every time I hear it starting up on my big ol' Grateful Dead digital jukebox. Drummerz having a BLAST, listening to each other, and driving the vibe, Phil just going to town, Brent sprouts two more hands in the middle there, while Bobby and Jerry just feed off each other. Just freaking HUGE. Crowd is in pure bliss as some of the tightest jamming is months is happening right there for them. I bet everyone was having an, "Is this going to end up a new road-built song?" moment. 
Glad this recording caught the Drums, as our Rhythm Devils were clearly ready to bring the curtain down on a composition that started 22 minutes ago. Tape flips happen, whatcha gon' do? 
Then I get teary again for Brent's most beautiful "I Will Take You Home," and then good gods have mercy, I'm utterly shocked to find myself honestly emotionally involved with August West for the very first time in my life, and well and truly so full of August's romantic righteousness, that the move into "Throwing Stones" seems perfectly right, and it all comes kicking out. There I am howling out loud with Bobby, "We are on our own." Not even a full moon tonight. Having been at DAR Constitution Hall on 08/17/95 with the Deadhead brother that got ME into the Dead in the 80s, those lines are sorta poignant to me. This version of the song is enormous, and the AUD recording is so good there is tons of headroom for that 7:30 assault of hard, deep lows.

Amazing show, high pitched recording at points. This show smokes through and through. You can tell the boys are feeling it. First set highlights for me include a beautiful Althea and an extremely energetic Cassidy. Second set speaks for itself. Brent adds so much here. Tunes that could have become stale like China Cat are revitalized by his playing. RIP.

This recording is good and I enjoy the crowd noise but it sounds very metallic to me. A lot of high pitch sounds that make parts hard to listen to. I prefer the Miller.
